{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3cf46a6a-002b-4356-bb2c-d0d2a1089c29","content":"TUnit is an MTP-native framework that uses `--treenode-filter` with a path pattern (`/assembly/namespace/class/test`). The command is:\n\n```\ndotnet test -- --treenode-filter \"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests\"\n```\n\nThe wildcards match any assembly and namespace, filtering to just the `SmsNotificationTests` class. This will run the two tests: `SendSms_HealthCheck` and `SendSms_ValidPhone_Succeeds`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"01a87663-a179-4f88-a666-196400d1935d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"This is a TUnit project. TUnit uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP) natively. For TUnit with MTP, the filter syntax is different from VSTest.\n\nTUnit uses its own `--treenode-filter` for filtering tests. To filter by class name, the syntax is:\n\n```\ndotnet run -- --treenode-filter \"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests\"\n```\n\nOr with `dotnet test`, TUnit on MTP uses `--filter` but the syntax depends on the platform. Let me check - TUnit 0.6.x uses MTP natively. With MTP, `dotnet test` passes through `--filter` but TUnit specifically uses `--treenode-filter`.\n\n\nWith `dotnet test` on newer .NET SDKs that support MTP, I can use a simpler filter syntax like `dotnet test --filter \"SmsNotificationTests\"`, though the recommended approach for TUnit remains the `--treenode-filter` option when running directly. single segment in the path pattern. So `/*/*/SmsNotificationTests` will match any assembly and namespace, then target the SmsNotificationTests class specifically. With `dotnet test` in .NET 9 and later, I can pass MTP-specific arguments after `--` to filter the tests correctly.","outputTokens":735,"requestId":"4C12:389019:7E02D1:9DA8D0:6A013156"},"id":"b70d8fb0-db72-4f10-a844-5e0742b6b882","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:31:19.492Z","parentId":"a77c211e-879f-4c70-9ffb-e8588a2fcf55"}
